    "title": "Core Concepts of Navigating the AWS Global Infrastructure",
    "lessonText": "Understanding the AWS Global Infrastructure is crucial for deploying and managing applications effectively.",
    "data": {
      "content": "The AWS Global Infrastructure is built around Regions and Availability Zones:\n\n*   **Regions:** Geographical areas containing multiple, isolated Availability Zones.\n*   **Availability Zones (AZs):** One or more discrete data centers, each with redundant power, networking, and connectivity, housed in separate facilities.\n*   **Benefits of Multiple AZs:**\n    *   **Fault Tolerance:** If one AZ fails, applications can failover to another AZ in the same Region.\n    *   **Low Latency:** Deploying applications closer to users reduces latency.\n    *   **Compliance:** Regions allow you to keep your data within a specific geographic area to meet compliance requirements.\n*   **Edge Locations:** AWS also utilizes Edge Locations for caching content through Amazon CloudFront, improving performance for end users globally."
